Comb Opt 3: Construction and Improvement Heuristics¶

Packages Used: Functions from the following packages are used below.

  • DataFrames
  • Random
  • XLSX

1. Need for Heuristics¶

The need to use heuristics is demonstrated for the QAP considered in Comb Opt 2. For the n = 7 kitchen layout example, the BIP formulation of QAP could easily find the global optimum. To see the limits of using just BIP, a larger instance (n = 25) is randomly generated. Both the W and D generated not non-symmetric and have zeros along their main diagonals.

Brute-Force Solution¶

In order to make a brute-force solution commensurate with the heuristic solution, the number of times the cost of a solution was evaluated in sdpi (i.e., TC was calculated) was output as cnt. This number of random solutions was then evaluated:

In [6]:
TC = Inf
for i = 1:res.cnt
    a = randperm(n)
    TCi = sum(W[a,a].*D)
    if TCi < TC
        TC = TCi
    end
end
TC
Out[6]:
147.36531669086665

Multistart¶

Finally, a multistart procedure can be used to find the best of n runs of sdpi:

In [7]:
include("myCombOptFunc.jl")
function sdpimultistart(W,D)
    n = size(W,1)
    TC = Inf
    for i = 1:n
        res = sdpi(randperm(n),W,D)
        if res.TC < TC
            (TC,a) = res
        end
    end
    return (TC,a)
end
Random.seed!(3242)
(TC,a) = sdpimultistart(W,D)
TC, a

(136.88790675024478, [18, 2, 13, 1, 9, 4, 6, 22, 19, 3  …  25, 21, 16, 10, 17, 20, 15, 12, 11, 8])

2. Heuristic Solutions¶

Heuristic procedures for problems in combinatorial optimization do not admit optimal solutions, only

  • A solution within some guaranteed bound of optimal (provable bound, optimality gap)
  • A best-known solution (stop running heuristic only when need to have a solution)

Heuristics: The computational effort is split between

  • Construction: construct a feasible solution
  • Improvement: find a better feasible solution

Easy construction (e.g., QAP, Traveling Salesman Problem):

  • Lack of constraints make any random point or permutation a feasible solution
  • It can then be improved, allowing construct-then-improve multiple times, or what is termed multistart

Hard construction (e.g., Bin Packing, Vehicle Routing Problem):

  • Almost no chance of generating a random feasible solution due to constraints on what is a feasible solution
  • Need to include randomness as a solution is generated in order to construct multiple different solutions (which "might" then be able to be improved)

Ex 1: QAP (see above)¶

  • Easy construction via random permutation
  • Easy improvement via SDPI

Ex 2: Bin Packing (see MIP 4)¶

  • Hard Construction via First-Fit
  • No easy improvement possible since we need to eliminate a bin to improve the solution

First-Fit Construction Heuristic for Bin Packing¶

"""
    firstfit(v,V)
First-fit heuristic for bin packing.

Returns array where each element is the indices of items from `v` in a bin. Each element of `v` is the weight of the item and each bin is packed so that its total weight of items does not exceed `V`.
"""
function firstfit(v,V)
    # Put first item into first bin
    B = [[1]]                  # Array of arrays
    b = [v[1]]                 # Array of scalars
    # Add remaining items to bins
    for i = 2:length(v)
        idx = findfirst(b .+ v[i] .<= V)    # Find first bin item fits into
        if ~isnothing(idx)                  # Found existing bin
            b[idx] += v[i]
            push!(B[idx],i)
        else                                # Create new bin for item
            push!(b,v[i])
            push!(B,[i])
        end
    end
    return B
end

Since it not possible to easily improve a constructed bin-packing solution, the only easy way to find alternate solutions is to include randomness by randomly re-ordering the items v used by firstfit multiple times and return the best constructed solution found:

In [10]:
include("myCombOptFunc.jl")
function multifirstfit(v,V)
    m = length(v)
    TC, B = Inf, 0
    for i = 1:m^2
        Bi = firstfit(v[randperm(m)],V)
        if length(Bi) < TC
            TC, B = length(Bi), Bi
        end
    end
    return (TC,B)
end
Random.seed!(46345)
(TC,B) = multifirstfit(v,V)
TC
Out[10]:
112

3. Improvement Heuristics¶

The solutions reached by an improvement heuristics define a local neighborhood that usually does not include all possible solutions, and the best solution found in the neighborhood is a local optimum. In order to expand the local neighborhood searched by a pairwise (or 2-way) interchange-type improvement procedure like SDPI, the types of interchanges can be expanded to include 3-way interchanges and r-way interchanges, in general.

The number of r-way interchanges of n objects is:

$ \begin{eqnarray} \quad I(n,r) &=& \begin{pmatrix} \mbox{number of ways } r \mbox{ objects can } \\ \mbox{be drawn from } n \mbox{ objects} \end{pmatrix} \times \begin{pmatrix} \mbox{number of derangements} \\ \mbox{of } r \mbox{ objects} \end{pmatrix} \\ &=& \dbinom{n}{r} \, !n = \frac{n!}{r!(n - r)!} \; r! \sum_{i=0}^{r} \frac{(-1)^i}{i!} = \frac{n!}{(n - r)!} \sum_{i=0}^{r} \frac{(-1)^i}{i!} \end{eqnarray}$

For $n = 3: I(3,2) + I(3,3) = 3 + 2 = 5 = n! -1$

Pairwise interchange graph¶

In order to illustrate the operation of the SDPI heuristic, a "pairwise interchange graph" can be constructed for small (i.e., less than five machines/sites) problems. In such a graph, each node represents one of the n! possible assignment arrays, and each arc represents a pairwise interchange that transforms assignment into another via an interchange of the elements at two positions. Each node is connected via arcs representing all of the possible pairwise interchanges from this assignment. The value assigned to each node is the total cost TC. Although the global optimum assignment can be read off the graph for small problems, there would be too many nodes to make this feasible for larger problems.

An this example, the pairwise interchange graph has 4! = 24 nodes corresponding to all of the possible assignments of 4 machines to 4 sites. The arc from _a_1 to _a_2 represents the interchange of machines 3 and 4 located at sites 3 and 4. The global optimum assignment is _a_18, corresponding to TC = 3,670.

4. QAP Ex: Slotting¶

Slotting refers to the assignment of items (a.k.a. stock-keeping units (SKUs)) to storage locations so that subsequent order picking operations are best supported. For case and piece picking, the basic idea is to assign frequently picked (fast) items to the most convenient pick locations and use demand correlation information to assign items that are picked together to locations that are close together. As shown below, the most convenient pick locations are those that are in the "golden zone" and those that are close to the takeaway conveyor:

Activity Profiling¶

Activity profiling is the systematic analysis of the items and orders handled in a warehouse in order to improve its design and operation. In the design of an order picking system, a representative set of customer orders are used together with the item master file to generate parameters that are used for a variety of different warehousing decisions, including equipment and method selection and slotting. If available, the previous three months to one year of customer orders provide a reasonably representative set of orders.

An example of activity profiling is presented in the figure above. Each customer order is composed of one or more lines, where each line represents an item–quantity pair (e.g., order 1 has five lines, with the first line indicating five units of item A have been ordered). In this example, the five customer orders along with the item master file are used to create the following warehouse design parameters:

  • Total Lines—the total number of lines for all items in all orders over some period of time (representative of total picking activity); used to select piece-picking methods.
  • Lines per Order—the average number of different items (i.e., lines or SKUs) in an order; used to select piece-picking method.
  • Cube per Order—the average total cubic volume of all of the units (i.e., pieces) in an order; used to select piece-picking methods.
  • Flow per Item—the total number of storage and retrieval operations performed for the item over some period of time; used to select pallet-picking equipment.
  • Lines per Item (a.k.a. popularity)—the total number of lines for the item in all orders over some period of time (representative of picking activity for item); used to select case- and piece-picking equipment and for slotting.
  • Cube Movement—the total unit demand of the item over some period of time times the cubic volume of each unit (representative of the cube in storage for the item); used to select pallet-, case-, and piece-picking equipment.
  • Demand Correlation—the percent (or just the number) of orders in which both items appear; used for zoning and slotting.

In the figure above, the item master file includes the dimensions, cubic volume, and weight of each item. Note that an item's cube can be less than the product of its dimensions (e.g., items C and D). In addition, the unit of measure (UOM) is typically included. The UOM is a description of whether the quantity of inventory for an item refers to individual units (eaches or pieces, EA), cases (CA), or pallets (PA). A conversion ratio is used whenever multiple units of measure are used for the same item.

Ex 4: 20-Order, 8-Item Linear Slotting¶

Three sets of representative customer order data and an item master file are in the spreadsheet ItemOrderData.xlsx (with length, width, and depth in inches; cube in cubic-inches; weight in pounds). The demand correlation distribution for the eight SKUs in the dataset in the worksheet OrderSet1 can be used to assign them to one of eight slots located in a linear sequence spaced one unit of distance apart. The worksheet has one row (or "line") for each order-sku pair (quantity and UOM data is not needed):
